In [12]:
def hist_box(data,col):
  f, (ax_box, ax_hist) = plt.subplots(2, sharex=True, gridspec_kw={'height_ratios': (0.15, 0.85)}, figsize=(12,6))
  # Adding a graph in each part
  sns.boxplot(data[col], ax=ax_box, showmeans=True)
  sns.distplot(data[col], ax=ax_hist)
  plt.show()

Observation: define a hist_box() function that provides both a boxplot and a histogram in the same visual, with which we can perform univariate analysis on the columns of this dataset.

In [13]:
def hist_box(col):
    fig, axs = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(10, 5))
    axs[0].hist(col, bins=10)
    axs[0].set_xlabel('Values')
    axs[0].set_ylabel('Frequency')
    axs[0].set_title('Histogram')
    axs[1].boxplot(col)
    axs[1].set_ylabel('Values')
    axs[1].set_title('Box Plot')
    plt.show()

In [30]:
def stacked_barplot(data,predictor,target,figsize=(10,6)):
  (pd.crosstab(data[predictor],data[target],normalize='index')*100).plot(kind='bar',figsize=figsize,stacked=True)
  plt.legend(loc="lower right")
  plt.ylabel('Percentage Cancellations %')

Observation: We will define a stacked barplot() function to help analyse how the target variable varies across predictor categories.

In [38]:
def metrics_score(actual, predicted):
    print(classification_report(actual, predicted))

    cm = confusion_matrix(actual, predicted)
    plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))
    
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True,  fmt='.2f', xticklabels=['Not Cancelled', 'Cancelled'], yticklabels=['Not Cancelled', 'Cancelled'])
    plt.ylabel('Actual')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted')
    plt.show()

Observation: Creating a function to calculate and print the classification report and confusion matrix so that we don't have to rewrite the same code repeatedly for each model.

Four Key Takeaways for Business Recommendations:

  1. When implementing a new strategy, external factors, such as the number of advertizations, lower prices, should also be carefully considered as our analysis shows that the customers who have been followed up when cancelling the Hotel Booking.
  2. Closer to the fall time, there are fewer cancellations compared to the other seasons of the year.
  3. Lower prices for the rates of the rooms and better quality of living will decrease the percentage of the amount of people that will cancel their hotel booking.
  4. Offer incentives for non-cancellation: Consider offering incentives such as discounts or complimentary amenities for guests who commit to their bookings and don't cancel. This should increase the amount of repeated guests as well.
